'''Melanie Lisa Jane Stiassny''' (born 17 January 1953 in Bielefeld, Germany) is the Axelrod Research Curator of [[Ichthyology]] at the [[American Museum of Natural History]]. Her research interests focus on freshwater biodiversity documentation and systematic ichthyology in the Old World tropics, including tropical Africa (especially in the [[Congo River]]) and Madagascar.<ref name="RGGS Faculty">{{cite web|title=RGGS Faculty|url=http://rggs.amnh.org/faculty/view/35|publisher=American Museum of Natural History|accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref> She has published broadly on the [[biogeography]] conservation and [[systematics]] of [[teleosts]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Fresh and Brackish Water Fishes of Lower Guinea, west-Central Africa|year=2007|publisher=IRD Éditions|location=Paris|isbn=2709916207}}</ref> Stiassny holds both a BS and a Ph.D. from [[King's College London]], and has previously taught at [[Harvard University]] and [[Columbia University]] and is now a professor in the [[Richard Gilder Graduate School]] at the [[American Museum of Natural History]]. She is a member of the National Council of the [[World Wildlife Fund]], the Advisory Council of [[Conservation International]]’s Center for Applied Biodiversity Science, the Advisory Board of [[National Geographic Society]]’s Conservation Trust.,<ref name="RGGS Faculty" /> and the Deutsche Cichliden Gesellschaft (DCG, German Cichlid Society).
She was honored with the creation of the [[Stiassnyiformes]] in recognition of her contributions to ichthyology and systematics.<ref name="Stiassnyiformes">{{cite journal |author2=Agnès Dettaï |author3=Corinne Cruaud |author4=Arnaud Couloux |author5=Martine Desoutter-Meniger |author6=Guillaume Lecointre |title=RNF213, a new nuclear marker for acanthomorph phylogeny|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|date=February 2009|volume=50|issue=2|pages=345–363|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2008.11.013|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790308005526|accessdate=15 March 2013|last1=Li|first1=Blaise |pmid=19059489}}</ref>
